thoughts.a: The input and output grids are the same sizes. The input grid is composed of a black background with what looks to be to a separate aqua objects, each containing room-like structures in them. Each room-like opening is a 3x3 square, with some door or passageway that connects each room-like structure to the next. Sometimes there are no such openings and a room is totally blocked off and inaccessible. Inside of each of these aqua structures one room is filled with pink tiles. In the output grid, we see that there are multiple room-like structures now filled with pink tiles, including a pink line acting as a bridge across the two aqua objects. So the hypothesis is the following. The input grid will contain a black color background and some number of aqua objects. These aqua objects will have room-like structures in them and potentially doors or openings that connect each room-like structure to the next. Additionally, inside these aqua objects, one room will be filled with some color, in this case pink. We need to traverse the rooms in the aqua objects, starting from one pink room and then going to the next until we connect with a pink bridge outside of each aqua object. Rooms that we traverse along the way are also filled with pink, as well as the doorways that connect the rooms are filled with pink. Any room that we do not use in order to connect the two aqua objects are not filled with pink.
thoughts.b: The input grid contains a black background and two aqua objects. These aqua objects have many room-like structures in them. Some of the rooms are totally seeled off. In this pair, we have yellow tiles that are filling in and acting as the starting points for the room-like objects. According to the hypothesis, we need to traverse the room-like structures and the openings in order to connect the two separate yellow sections. Whenever we use a room in an aqua object and traverse it, that room is changed to yellow in the output grid. Additional information in this pair is that what happens when the openings of the two separate aqua objects are not directly in line with each other. In the previous pair, they were, and therefore we only needed to make one single line of pink. In this pair, they are not aligned with each other. So how do we draw the yellow line to connect to them? Well, according to this input-output pair, we need to fill in the entire section, up to and including the door for each of the rooms of each of the exit openings in the aquare objects. Note that we don't go beyond the last external door. The rest of the background remains black. This pair gave us additional information about how to handle the cases where the final opening is not aligned with the other opening of the other aqua object.
thoughts.c: The input grid again has a black color background with two aqua objects. These aqua objects have room-like structures in them, where some of them are totally sealed off. According to the hypothesis, We need to identify the starting point color in each aqua object. In this case, it's green. The goal then is to traverse the room-like structure in order to connect the two green starting points inside of different aqua objects. Whenever we encounter a room that we traverse, the output grid should change that room to be entirely green, including the doorways that connect between the rooms. Any room that we do not traverse does not change to green. Additionally, when we get to the external part of the aqua object, We fill in the entire section that connects from the external door to the other external door or opening.  We do not fill in with green anything past these doors. This is what is shown in the output grid, and thus the hypothesis holds.
